content: I'm pretty new to making music in general, but I've been making all the music for my video game on my tablet, on sunvox. It's easy to pick up, super flexible, and the online community for it is incredibly helpful despite its small size.
Why is this app monitoring emails ? Clicking on an email attachment opened this app. This is suspicious behaviour, so uninstalled sunvox.
replyContent: SunVox does not monitor your emails. Now it's optimized for Android 10. Unfortunately, some versions of the system (and some file browsers) don't always work correctly with the import filter of the app. So any binary file can be opened as a raw sample by SunVox, if you have not specified another default app.

The tracker is back... and it's brought some new guns. Those who remember 
the early days of digital music on Amiga and Atari, with Octamed and such 
like, will recognise the scrolling plethora of numbers in patterns. But 
this has a modern twist. As many channels as you need, effects like 
side-chain compression, a sequencer to construct your song in a more 
tactile fashion... and it runs on my mobile and my PC. Amazing app. Update: 
I still play with this. It keeps getting better. I don't use PC these days 
but the app works with the phone docked in Dex at 4K. Recently discovered 
it also works with Gear VR Labs for a workspace as large as you want it.

Great work, and it maintains quality across many platforms. Getting into 
trackers is not easy - the idiom is not intuitive at all, even if trackers 
were important to the development of music software. SunVox makes the 
learning curve as easy as it can be, and it is much more than a tracker. It 
is a virtual synthesizer studio in your pocket. Fabulous sound flows from 
the app, as it does on other platforms, but on an Android phone this is 
especially unusual and worthy of gratitude. Thank you for making Android a 
warmer place.

I've been using this app for five years. I've used it on PC, Mac, iOS, and Android, and the functionality and reliability are all the same. The only real learning curve is in the functions of the different modules; I have been making full-fledged compositions since the first day I had it. I have just bought my fourth phone in that time period and reinstalled the app, and thought I'd show my support. Thank you, Mr Zolotov, for your wonderful little creation.

For all the hype, I'm sorely disappointed by how horribly slow the pattern-creation process is. JUST to replicate a chunk of a pattern, you have to 1. open the menu, 2. press "selection begin," 3. scroll to where you want (which is weird because dragging your finger down moves the screen DOWN instead of up), 4. open the menu, 5. press "selection end," 6. open the menu, 7. press "duplicate." MidSequer can do this with one press-hold-drag, then copy and paste. I really hope SunVox gets a piano roll feature added; that would bring me back instantly.

This app is one of the best I have ever encountered. I can transfer projects between this device and my windows/raspberry pi/iPad (in my case using dropbox) and I can open them and continue where I left off! I highly recommend the app anyway (recursive meta-modules now make it incredibly powerful, and patch creation on a small touchscreen device is still very fun), but ESPECIALLY advise using it in conjunction with a desktop install, as keyboard entry for making patterns in the editor is so much easier, especially on a larger screen. If you are in two minds, just watch a YouTube tutorial or two and I'm pretty sure you'll be sold. It is really not as hard as it might seem at first glance, just very very powerful!

It has great sounds and a very clever interface design with sliding panels that scale to any display size and with something reminiscent of a modular synthesizer, but in the end it is more toy than tool with missing support for MIDI input on Android and intentionally pixelated graphics that's putting nostalgia before usability, effectively lowering your device resolution by an order of magnitude necessitating an excessively flat and therefore very confusing interface. I would gladly rate this five stars if it enabled MIDI input and made more efficient use of modern high-density displays, alas I fear at least the latter issue is a point of pride and philosophy the developer is unlikely to back on.

content: OMFG He did it. It exists.

Really is the most powerful music creation tool on Android.  Coming from Ableton and FL Studio, the interface was initially overwhelming, but spending some time with the manual and YouTube tutorials helped me a lot.  It wasn't until I started transferring my projects from PC to my tablet that I realized that no other app else really comes close to how much you can do with this.  You can make way, way more than just chiptune style music with this.  MIDI input support would make this perfect, and if that's asking a lot perhaps a touch-friendly interface for the Sampler with playable drum pads would work very nicely.

About the only thing missing is midi input but then again midi on android is a pain in the butt due to lack of a os level api for it thus forcing devs to use hacky workaround solutions that may or may not work on all devices. If native midi via usb host is not practical perhaps midi via wifi would me a good fall back.

Before buying the app on my SGS4, I tried the Windows version. It has a pretty slick set of synthesizers and effects, clearly aimed toward "chiptune" style music generation. There are also quite a few digital samples, more than enough for basic composition tasks.   I was concerned because the screenshots make the screen look pretty cluttered, but you can resize or move most of the elements with no trouble, so I had no problem composing a simple video game soundtrack on my first use of the program.  My only complaint is with some basic UI elements: In the note strip at the top of the screen, moving your finger up moves the items on the screen down, exactly the opposite of what you'd expect. Likewise, the file picker doesn't finger-scroll like other Android/iOS touch apps. (Instead, it has a classic scroll bar on the right. Kind of anti-pattern, IMO.) You also can't scrub in the timeline, but these are minor quirks.  Aside from the UI quirks, this is a fun and easy program to compose on, and with something like Google Drive or Dropbox, you can wirelessly sync files between your phone (or tablet) and a PC. That makes this an even more valuable tool.
i managed to do beautiful stuff with it! good job

I've been looking for a functional tracker like the ones from the old days of the Commodore Amiga, but I couldn't find anything that suited my needs. The famous counterpart, Caustic, is nice, but I didn't feel like it was the right software for me. I finally decided to buy Sunvox, even though the video in the play store doesn't give justice to its beauty. It's amazing. It's the perfect tracker for android, if you care to make 8bit music (but not only!). The interface can be a bit strange, but you'll love it
It's good just it should come with a tutorial
Great!
Very in depth synth for any user whose determined to take advantage. I use this with gstomper and caustic 2. Flawless.

Being familiar with the trackers like NitroTracker for the DS and MilkyTracker on PC, I was comfortable composing on it, however I can understand that it's hard to grasp the tracker concept at first if you're used to usual way of composing like in Logic Pro, Cubase, Live etc, and using it on a touch-screen compounds the trickiness. Once you're used it, it's not that hard, bit like riding a bike for the first time.  But the idea of using most modern compositional tools like samplers and synths as well as virtual processing tools such as EQ and compression makes this one of the best on-the-go composition tools I've ever come across. It even has automation! Also, with it being cross-platform, whatever I compose on Android I can just sync SunVox files across to SunVox on my PC with no issues whatsoever.  It borrows all the usual tracker elements like note effects and embedding samples into the files. Once I was used the interface I can scratch down any ideas that come into my head into SunVox in minutes, it makes my commute to and from work bearable ha!  Overall, it's great value, it's flexible and powerful!

I own and frequently use all of the top tier music production applications on Android (G-Stomper Beat Studio, Caustic, Su-Preme MPA), also including both Pixitracker applications and both synthesizers by this developer.  And I fully understand how to use all of those applications, and pretty much most DAW's, Drum Machines and Synthesizers.  But, for whatever reason, I still cannot fully grasp how to use SunVox.  The entry point into understanding and fully utilizing this robust application still perplexes me to the point of frustration.  Maybe I just haven't given this app a fair shot and sat down long enough to understand how it works.  But on the other side of that confusing coin, I have read through the tutorial and watched the how-to videos (though, I find those in particular to be extremely lacking and not intuitive at all), and I still come away with being stumped as it pertains to being comfortable with this application.  I realize that some of the best and most powerful tools require a lot of study and have a large learning curve.  But this app, to me, is just overly complicated, when I don't believe it needs to be this way to be a great app.
I love it! Not much more to say.
